[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Cypher was largely an invention of Andrés Taylor while working for Neo4j, Inc.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Cypher was originally intended to be used with the graph database Neo4j, but was opened up through the openCypher project in October 2015.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] The language was designed with the power and capability of SQL (standard query language for the relational database model) in mind, but Cypher was based on the components and needs of a database built upon the concepts of graph theory.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] In a graph model, data is structured as nodes (vertices in math and network science) and relationships (edges in math and network science) to focus on how entities in the data are connected and related to one another.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Cypher is based on the Property Graph Model, which organizes data into nodes and edges (called “relationships” in Cypher).
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] In addition to those standard graph elements of nodes and relationships, the property graph model adds labels and properties for describing finer categories and attributes of the data.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] They can hold any number of attributes (key-value pairs) called properties.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Nodes can be tagged with zero or more labels (like tags or categories), representing their different roles in a domain.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Relationships provide directed, named, semantically-relevant connections between two node entities.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] A relationship always has a direction, a start node, an end node, and exactly one relationship type.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Like nodes, relationships can also have properties.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Labels can group similar nodes together by assigning zero or more node labels.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Labels are kind of like tags and allow you to specify certain types of entities to look for or create.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Properties are key-value pairs with a binding of a string key and some value from the Cypher type system.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Cypher queries are assembled with patterns of nodes and relationships with any specified filtering on labels and properties to create, read, update, delete data found in the specified pattern.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] The Cypher's data type system includes many of the common data types used in other programming and query languages.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Supported data types include scalar value types such as boolean, string, number, integer, and floating-point numbers.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] It also supports temporal types like `datetime`, `localdatetime`, date, time, localtime, and duration.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Container data types for maps and lists are available, along with graph types for node, relationship, path, and a void type.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] The Cypher query language depicts patterns of nodes and relationships and filters those patterns based on labels and properties.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Cypher’s syntax is based on ASCII art, which is text-based visual art for computers.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] This makes the language very visual and easy to read because it both visually and structurally represents the data specified in the query.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] For instance, nodes are represented with parentheses around the attributes and information regarding the entity.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Relationships are depicted with an arrow (either directed or undirected) with the relationship type in brackets.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Similar to other query languages, Cypher contains a variety of keywords for specifying patterns, filtering patterns, and returning results.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Among those most common are: MATCH, WHERE, and RETURN.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] These operate slightly differently than the SELECT and WHERE in SQL; however, they have similar purposes.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] MATCH is used before describing the search pattern for finding nodes, relationships, or combinations of nodes and relationships together.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] WHERE in Cypher is used to add additional constraints to patterns and filter out any unwanted patterns.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Cypher’s RETURN formats and organizes how the results should be outputted.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Just as with other query languages, you can return the results with specific properties, lists, ordering, and more.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] The WHERE clause then filters to only keep patterns where the Movie node in the match clause has a year property that is less than the value of the parameter passed in.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] In the return, the query specifies to output the movie nodes that fit the pattern and filtering from the match and where clauses.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Cypher also contains keywords to specify clauses for writing, updating, and deleting data.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] CREATE and DELETE are used to create and delete nodes and relationships.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] SET and REMOVE are used to set values to properties and add/delete labels on nodes.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] MERGE is used to create nodes uniquely without duplicates.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Nodes can only be deleted when they have no other relationships still existing.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] With the openCypher project, an effort began to standardize Cypher as the query language for graph processing.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] As part of this process there have been five face-to-face openCypher Implementers Meetings (oCIMs).
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] The first meeting took place in February 2017 at SAP's headquarters in Walldorf in Germany, coincident with a meeting of the Linked Data Benchmark Council.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] The most recent OCIM took place in Berlin, coincident with the W3C Workshop on Web Standards for Graph Data Management, in March 2019.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] At that meeting, there was a consensus to work towards Cypher becoming a significant input into a wider project for an international standardized Graph Query Language called GQL.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] In September 2019, a proposal for a GQL standard project was approved by a vote of national standards bodies which are members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1 (responsible for information technology standards).
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] As of 2024, the GQL Standard has been published as the standard graph query language under ISO/IEC 39075:2024.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] The first open-source implementation of a subset of the language is already available.
[src:memgraph/cypher-query-language] Aside from the implementation, one can also find a formalization and read the syntax of the specific subset of GQL.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A **graph database** (**GDB**) is a database that uses graph structures for semantic queries with nodes, edges, and properties to represent and store data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A key concept of the system is the graph (or edge or relationship).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The graph relates the data items in the store to a collection of nodes and edges, the edges representing the relationships between the nodes.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The relationships allow data in the store to be linked together directly and, in many cases, retrieved with one operation.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases hold the relationships between data as a priority.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Querying relationships is fast because they are perpetually stored in the database.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Relationships can be intuitively visualized using graph databases, making them useful for heavily inter-connected data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are commonly referred to as a NoSQL database.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are similar to 1970s network model databases in that both represent general graphs, but network-model databases operate at a lower level of abstraction and lack easy traversal over a chain of edges.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The underlying storage mechanism of graph databases can vary.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Relationships are first-class citizens in a graph database and can be labeled, directed, and given properties.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and store the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes a level of abstraction between the graph database management system and physical storage devices).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Others use a key–value store or document-oriented database for storage, making them inherently NoSQL structures.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] As of 2021, no graph query language has been universally adopted in the same way as SQL was for relational databases.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] There is a wide variety of systems used, many of which are tightly tied to one product.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Early standardization efforts led to multi-vendor query languages like Gremlin, SPARQL, and Cypher.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In September 2019 a proposal for a project to create a new standard graph query language (ISO/IEC 39075 Information Technology — Database Languages — GQL) was approved by members of ISO/IEC Joint Technical Committee 1(ISO/IEC JTC 1).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] GQL is intended to be a declarative database query language, like SQL.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In addition to having query language interfaces, some graph databases are accessed through application programming interfaces (APIs).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases differ from graph compute engines.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are technologies that are translations of the relational online transaction processing (OLTP) databases.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] On the other hand, graph compute engines are used in online analytical processing (OLAP) for bulk analysis.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases attracted considerable attention in the 2000s, due to the successes of major technology corporations using proprietary graph databases, along with the introduction of open-source graph databases.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] One study concluded that an RDBMS was "comparable" in performance to existing graph analysis engines at executing graph queries.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In the mid-1960s, navigational databases such as IBM's IMS supported tree-like structures in its hierarchical model, but the strict tree structure could be circumvented with virtual records.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph structures could be represented in network model databases from the late 1960s.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] CODASYL, which had defined COBOL in 1959, defined the Network Database Language in 1969.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Labeled graphs could be represented in graph databases from the mid-1980s, such as the Logical Data Model.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Commercial object databases (ODBMSs) emerged in the early 1990s.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In 2000, the Object Data Management Group published a standard language for defining object and relationship (graph) structures in their ODMG'93 publication.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In the mid-to-late 2000s, commercial graph databases with ACID guarantees such as Neo4j and Oracle Spatial and Graph became available.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In the 2010s, commercial ACID graph databases that could be scaled horizontally became available.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Further, SAP HANA brought in-memory and columnar technologies to graph databases.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Also in the 2010s, multi-model databases that supported graph models (and other models such as relational database or document-oriented database) became available, such as OrientDB, ArangoDB, and MarkLogic (starting with its 7.0 version).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] During this time, graph databases of various types have become especially popular with social network analysis with the advent of social media companies.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Also during the decade, cloud-based graph databases such as Amazon Neptune and Neo4j AuraDB became available.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Based on graph theory, graph databases store data in a way that reflects how it is conceptually understood, using nodes to represent entities and edges to represent the relationships between them.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] It consists of a set of objects, such as a node or an edge.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A labeled-property graph model is represented by a set of nodes, relationships, properties, and labels.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Both nodes of data and their relationships are named and can store properties represented by key–value pairs.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The edges representing the relationships have two qualities: they always have a start node and an end node, and are directed; making the graph a directed graph.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] This is useful in providing additional metadata and semantics to relationships of the nodes.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Direct storage of relationships allows a constant-time traversal.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In an RDF graph model, each addition of information is represented with a separate node.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, imagine a scenario where a user has to add a name property for a person represented as a distinct node in the graph.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In a labeled-property graph model, this would be done with an addition of a name property into the node of the person.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] However, in an RDF, the user has to add a separate node called `hasName` connecting it to the original person node.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Specifically, an RDF graph model is composed of nodes and arcs.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] An RDF graph notation or a statement is represented by: a node for the subject, a node for the object, and an arc for the predicate.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A node may be left blank, a literal and/or be identified by a URI.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A literal for a node may be of two types: plain (untyped) and typed.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A plain literal has a lexical form and optionally a language tag.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A typed literal is made up of a string with a URI that identifies a particular datatype.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A blank node may be used to accurately illustrate the state of the data when the data does not have a URI.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are a powerful tool for graph-like queries.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, computing the shortest path between two nodes in the graph.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Other graph-like queries can be performed over a graph database in a natural way (for example graph's diameter computations or community detection).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graphs are flexible, meaning it allows the user to insert new data into the existing graph without loss of application functionality.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] There is no need for the designer of the database to plan out extensive details of the database's future use cases.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Some depend on a relational engine and "store" the graph data in a table (although a table is a logical element, therefore this approach imposes another level of abstraction between the graph database, the graph database management system and the physical devices where the data is actually stored).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A node would be represented as any other document store, but edges that link two different nodes hold special attributes inside its document; a _from and _to attributes.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Data lookup performance is dependent on the access speed from one particular node to another.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Because index-free adjacency enforces the nodes to have direct physical RAM addresses and physically point to other adjacent nodes, it results in a fast retrieval.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A native graph system with index-free adjacency does not have to move through any other type of data structures to find links between the nodes.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Directly related nodes in a graph are stored in the cache once one of the nodes are retrieved, making the data lookup even faster than the first time a user fetches a node.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] However, such advantage comes at a cost.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Index-free adjacency sacrifices the efficiency of queries that do not use graph traversals.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Native graph databases use index-free adjacency to process CRUD operations on the stored data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Multiple categories of graphs by kind of data have been recognised.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Codd's 1970 paper on the relational model, relational databases have been the de facto industry standard for large-scale data storage systems.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Relational models require a strict schema and data normalization which separates data into many tables and removes any duplicate data within the database.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Data is normalized in order to preserve data consistency and support ACID transactions.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] However this imposes limitations on how relationships can be queried.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] One of the relational model's design motivations was to achieve a fast row-by-row access.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Problems arise when there is a need to form complex relationships between the stored data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Although relationships can be analyzed with the relational model, complex queries performing many join operations on many different attributes over several tables are required.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In working with relational models, foreign key constraints should also be considered when retrieving relationships, causing additional overhead.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Compared with relational databases, graph databases are often faster for associative data sets and map more directly to the structure of object-oriented applications.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] They can scale more naturally to large datasets as they do not typically need join operations, which can often be expensive.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] As they depend less on a rigid schema, they are marketed as more suitable to manage ad hoc and changing data with evolving schemas.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Conversely, relational database management systems are typically faster at performing the same operation on large numbers of data elements, permitting the manipulation of the data in its natural structure.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Despite the graph databases' advantages and recent popularity over relational databases, it is recommended the graph model itself should not be the sole reason to replace an existing relational database.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A graph database may become relevant if there is an evidence for performance improvement by orders of magnitude and lower latency.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The relational model gathers data together using information in the data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, one might look for all the "users" whose phone number contains the area code "311".
[src:memgraph/graph-database] This would be done by searching selected datastores, or tables, looking in the selected phone number fields for the string "311".
[src:memgraph/graph-database] This can be a time-consuming process in large tables, so relational databases offer indexes, which allow data to be stored in a smaller sub-table, containing only the selected data and a unique key (or primary key) of the record.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] If the phone numbers are indexed, the same search would occur in the smaller index table, gathering the keys of matching records, and then looking in the main data table for the records with those keys.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Usually, a table is stored in a way that allows a lookup via a key to be very fast.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Relational databases do not *inherently* contain the idea of fixed relationships between records.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Instead, related data is linked to each other by storing one record's unique key in another record's data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, a table containing email addresses for users might hold a data item called `userpk`, which contains the primary key of the user record it is associated with.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] This operation, termed a join, can be computationally expensive.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Depending on the complexity of the query, the number of joins, and indexing various keys, the system may have to search through multiple tables and indexes and then sort it all to match it together.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In contrast, graph databases directly store the relationships between records.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Instead of an email address being found by looking up its user's key in the `userpk` column, the user record contains a pointer that directly refers to the email address record.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] That is, having selected a user, the pointer can be followed directly to the email records, there is no need to search the email table to find the matching records.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] This can eliminate the costly join operations.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, if one searches for all of the email addresses for users in area code "311", the engine would first perform a conventional search to find the users in "311", but then retrieve the email addresses by following the links found in those records.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] A relational database would first find all the users in "311", extract a list of the primary keys, perform another search for any records in the email table with those primary keys, and link the matching records together.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For these types of common operations, graph databases would theoretically be faster.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The true value of the graph approach becomes evident when one performs searches that are more than one level deep.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, consider a search for users who have "subscribers" (a table linking users to other users) in the "311" area code.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In this case a relational database has to first search for all the users with an area code in "311", then search the subscribers table for any of those users, and then finally search the users table to retrieve the matching users.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In contrast, a graph database would search for all the users in "311", then follow the backlinks through the subscriber relationship to find the subscriber users.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] This avoids several searches, look-ups, and the memory usage involved in holding all of the temporary data from multiple records needed to construct the output.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In terms of big O notation, this query would be $O(\log n)+O(1)$ time – i.e., proportional to the logarithm of the size of the data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In contrast, the relational version would be multiple $O(\log n)$ lookups, plus the $O(n)$ time needed to join all of the data records.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The relative advantage of graph retrieval grows with the complexity of a query.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, one might want to know "that movie about submarines with the actor who was in that movie with that other actor that played the lead in *Gone With the Wind*".
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In a relational database, this would require several separate searches through the movies and actors tables, doing another search on submarine movies, finding all the actors in those movies, and then comparing the (large) collected results.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In contrast, the graph database would walk from *Gone With the Wind* to Clark Gable, gather the links to the movies he has been in, gather the links out of those movies to other actors, and then follow the links out of those actors back to the list of movies.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The resulting list of movies can then be searched for "submarine".
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Relational databases are very well suited to flat data layouts, where relationships between data are only one or two levels deep.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For example, an accounting database might need to look up all the line items for all the invoices for a given customer, a three-join query.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] Graph databases are aimed at datasets that contain many more links.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] They are especially well suited to social networking systems, where the "friends" relationship is essentially unbounded.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] These properties make graph databases naturally suited to types of searches that are increasingly common in online systems, and in big data environments.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] For this reason, graph databases are becoming very popular for large online systems like Facebook, Google, Twitter, and similar systems with deep links between records.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] To further illustrate, imagine a relational model with two tables: a `people` table (which has a `person_id` and `person_name` column) and a `friend` table (with `friend_id` and `person_id`, which is a foreign key from the `people` table).
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In this case, searching for all of Jack's friends would result in the following SQL query.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] The above examples are a simple illustration of a basic relationship query.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] They condense the idea of relational models' query complexity that increases with the total amount of data.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] In comparison, a graph database query is easily able to sort through the relationship graph to present the results.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] There are also results that indicate simple, condensed, and declarative queries of the graph databases do not necessarily provide good performance in comparison to the relational databases.
[src:memgraph/graph-database] While graph databases offer an intuitive representation of data, relational databases offer better results when set operations are needed.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] An **in-memory database** (**IMDb**, or **main memory database system** (**MMDB**) or **memory resident database**) is a database management system that primarily relies on main memory for computer data storage.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] It is contrasted with database management systems that employ a disk storage mechanism.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] In-memory databases are faster than disk-optimized databases because disk access is slower than memory access and the internal optimization algorithms are simpler and execute fewer CPU instructions.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Accessing data in memory eliminates seek time when querying the data, which provides faster and more predictable performance than disk.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Applications where response time is critical, such as those running telecommunications network equipment and mobile advertising networks, often use main-memory databases.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] IMDBs have gained much traction, especially in the data analytics space, starting in the mid-2000s – mainly due to multi-core processors that can address large memory and due to less expensive RAM.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] A potential technical hurdle with in-memory data storage is the volatility of RAM.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Specifically in the event of a power loss, intentional or otherwise, data stored in volatile RAM is lost.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] With the introduction of non-volatile random-access memory technology, in-memory databases will be able to run at full speed and maintain data in the event of power failure.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] In its simplest form, main memory databases store data on volatile memory devices.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] These devices lose all stored information when the device loses power or is reset.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] In this case, IMDBs can be said to lack support for the "durability" portion of the ACID (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) properties.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Volatile memory-based IMDBs can, and often do, support the other three ACID properties of atomicity, consistency and isolation.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] While storing data in-memory confers performance advantages, it is an expensive method of data storage.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] An approach to realising the benefits of in-memory storage while limiting its costs is to store the most frequently accessed data in-memory and the rest on disk.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Since there is no hard distinction between which data should be stored in-memory and which should be stored on disk, some systems dynamically update where data is stored based on the data's usage.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] This approach is subtly different from caching, in which the most *recently accessed* data is cached, as opposed to the most *frequently accessed* data being stored in-memory.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] In the cloud computing industry the terms "data temperature", or "hot data" and "cold data" have emerged to describe how data is stored in this respect.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Hot data is used to describe mission-critical data that needs to be accessed frequently while cold data describes data that is needed less often and less urgently, such as data kept for archiving or auditing purposes.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Hot data should be stored in ways offering fast retrieval and modification, often accomplished by in-memory storage but not always.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Cold data on the other hand can be stored in a more cost-effective way and is accepted that data access will likely be slower compared to hot data.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] While these descriptions are useful, "hot" and "cold" lack concrete definitions.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Manufacturing efficiency provides another reason for selecting a combined in-memory/on-disk database system.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Some device product lines, especially in consumer electronics, include some units with permanent storage, and others that rely on memory for storage (set-top boxes, for example).
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] If such devices require a database system, a manufacturer can adopt a hybrid database system at lower and *upper* cost, and with less customization of code, rather than using separate in-memory and on-disk databases, respectively, for its disk-less and disk-based products.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] The first database engine to support both in-memory and on-disk tables in a single database, WebDNA, was released in 1995.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] Another variation involves large amounts of nonvolatile memory in the server, for example, flash memory chips as addressable memory rather than structured as disk arrays.
[src:memgraph/in-memory-database] A database in this form of memory combines very fast access speed with persistence over reboots and power losses.
[src:memgraph/nosql] NoSQL databases are popular in big data and real-time web applications due to their simple design, ability to scale across clusters of machines (called horizontal scaling), and precise control over data availability.
[src:memgraph/nosql] These structures can speed up certain tasks and are often considered more adaptable than fixed database tables.
[src:memgraph/nosql] However, many NoSQL systems prioritize speed and availability over strict consistency (per the CAP theorem), using eventual consistency—where updates reach all nodes eventually, typically within milliseconds, but may cause brief delays in accessing the latest data, known as stale reads.
[src:memgraph/nosql] While most lack full ACID transaction support, some, like MongoDB, include it as a key feature.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Barriers to wider NoSQL adoption include their use of low-level query languages instead of SQL, inability to perform ad hoc joins across tables, lack of standardized interfaces, and significant investments already made in relational databases.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Some NoSQL systems risk losing data through lost writes or other forms, though features like write-ahead logging—a method to record changes before they’re applied—can help prevent this.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Limitations within the interface environment are overcome using semantic virtualization protocols, such that NoSQL services are accessible to most operating systems.
[src:memgraph/nosql] The term *NoSQL* was used by Carlo Strozzi in 1998 to name his lightweight Strozzi NoSQL open-source relational database that did not expose the standard Structured Query Language (SQL) interface, but was still relational.
[src:memgraph/nosql] His NoSQL RDBMS is distinct from the around-2009 general concept of NoSQL databases.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Strozzi suggests that, because the current NoSQL movement "departs from the relational model altogether, it should therefore have been called more appropriately 'NoREL'", referring to "not relational".
[src:memgraph/nosql] Johan Oskarsson, then a developer at Last.fm, reintroduced the term *NoSQL* in early 2009 when he organized an event to discuss "open-source distributed, non-relational databases".
[src:memgraph/nosql] The name attempted to label the emergence of an increasing number of non-relational, distributed data stores, including open source clones of Google's Bigtable/MapReduce and Amazon's DynamoDB.
[src:memgraph/nosql] There are various ways to classify NoSQL databases, with different categories and subcategories, some of which overlap.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Key–value (KV) stores use the associative array (also called a map or dictionary) as their fundamental data model.
[src:memgraph/nosql] In this model, data is represented as a collection of key–value pairs, such that each possible key appears at most once in the collection.
[src:memgraph/nosql] The key–value model is one of the simplest non-trivial data models, and richer data models are often implemented as an extension of it.
[src:memgraph/nosql] The key–value model can be extended to a discretely ordered model that maintains keys in lexicographic order.
[src:memgraph/nosql] This extension is computationally powerful, in that it can efficiently retrieve selective key *ranges*.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Key–value stores can use consistency models ranging from eventual consistency to serializability.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Some databases support ordering of keys.
[src:memgraph/nosql] There are various hardware implementations, and some users store data in memory (RAM), while others on solid-state drives (SSD) or rotating disks (aka hard disk drive (HDD)).
[src:memgraph/nosql] The central concept of a document store is that of a "document".
[src:memgraph/nosql] While the details of this definition differ among document-oriented databases, they all assume that documents encapsulate and encode data (or information) in some standard formats or encodings.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Encodings in use include XML, YAML, and JSON and binary forms like BSON.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Documents are addressed in the database via a unique *key* that represents that document.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Another defining characteristic of a document-oriented database is an API or query language to retrieve documents based on their contents.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Compared to relational databases, collections could be considered analogous to tables and documents analogous to records.
[src:memgraph/nosql] But they are different – every record in a table has the same sequence of fields, while documents in a collection may have fields that are completely different.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Graph databases are designed for data whose relations are well represented as a graph consisting of elements connected by a finite number of relations.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Examples of data include social relations, public transport links, road maps, network topologies, etc.
[src:memgraph/nosql] The performance of NoSQL databases is usually evaluated using the metric of throughput, which is measured as operations per second.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Performance evaluation must pay attention to the right benchmarks such as production configurations, parameters of the databases, anticipated data volume, and concurrent user workloads.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Performance and scalability comparisons are most commonly done using the YCSB benchmark.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Since most NoSQL databases lack ability for joins in queries, the database schema generally needs to be designed differently.
[src:memgraph/nosql] There are three main techniques for handling relational data in a NoSQL database.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Instead of retrieving all the data with one query, it is common to do several queries to get the desired data.
[src:memgraph/nosql] NoSQL queries are often faster than traditional SQL queries, so the cost of additional queries may be acceptable.
[src:memgraph/nosql] If an excessive number of queries would be necessary, one of the other two approaches is more appropriate.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Instead of only storing foreign keys, it is common to store actual foreign values along with the model's data.
[src:memgraph/nosql] For example, each blog comment might include the username in addition to a user id, thus providing easy access to the username without requiring another lookup.
[src:memgraph/nosql] When a username changes, however, this will now need to be changed in many places in the database.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Thus this approach works better when reads are much more common than writes.
[src:memgraph/nosql] With document databases like MongoDB it is common to put more data in a smaller number of collections.
[src:memgraph/nosql] For example, in a blogging application, one might choose to store comments within the blog post document, so that with a single retrieval one gets all the comments.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Thus in this approach a single document contains all the data needed for a specific task.
[src:memgraph/nosql] A database is marked as supporting ACID properties (atomicity, consistency, isolation, durability) or join operations if the documentation for the database makes that claim.
[src:memgraph/nosql] However, this doesn't necessarily mean that the capability is fully supported in a manner similar to most SQL databases.
[src:memgraph/nosql] MongoDB did not support joining from a sharded collection until version 5.1.
[src:memgraph/nosql] OrientDB can resolve 1:1 joins using links by storing direct links to foreign records.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Different NoSQL databases, such as DynamoDB, MongoDB, Cassandra, Couchbase, HBase, and Redis, exhibit varying behaviors when querying non-indexed fields.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Many perform full-table or collection scans for such queries, applying filtering operations after retrieving data.
[src:memgraph/nosql] However, modern NoSQL databases often incorporate advanced features to optimize query performance.
[src:memgraph/nosql] For example, MongoDB supports compound indexes and query-optimization strategies, Cassandra offers secondary indexes and materialized views, and Redis employs custom indexing mechanisms tailored to specific use cases.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Systems like Elasticsearch use inverted indexes for efficient text-based searches, but they can still require full scans for non-indexed fields.
[src:memgraph/nosql] This behavior reflects the design focus of many NoSQL systems on scalability and efficient key-based operations rather than optimized querying for arbitrary fields.
[src:memgraph/nosql] Consequently, while these databases excel at basic CRUD operations and key-based lookups, their suitability for complex queries involving joins or non-indexed filtering varies depending on the database type—document, key–value, wide-column, or graph—and the specific implementation.
[src:memgraph/page] Memgraph is an open-source graph database built for streaming and compatible with Neo4j.
[src:memgraph/page] Learn how to utilize Memgraph to migrate and analyze your data.
[src:memgraph/page] To get started with Memgraph, explore everything the Memgraph ecosystem offers, including Memgraph Lab, Memgraph Cloud, MAGE graph library and more.
[src:memgraph/page] To start using Memgraph in your application, use one of the following client libraries and follow their getting started guide.
[src:memgraph/page] You can migrate your data from an existing graph or SQL database using CSV or JSON files, and import data using queries within a CYPHERL file.
[src:memgraph/page] You can query Memgraph using Cypher query language, use algorithms available in Memgraph’s MAGE library on your graph, and explore visualizations and query your data using Memgraph Lab.
[src:memgraph/page] Whether you are running Memgraph on-prem or in production, here are the fundamental concepts of how the database operates and the tools you need to configure it to your needs.
[src:memgraph/page] Explore deployment guides to run Memgraph across various environments, including Docker, native Linux, Kubernetes and cloud platforms like AWS, Azure and GCP.
[src:memgraph/page] Learn best practices, optimize for specific workloads and benchmark performance to ensure your graph applications scale efficiently in production.
[src:memgraph/page] New releases might affect your existing code, queries or configuration.
[src:memgraph/page] Ensure alignment with the latest updates and changes.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memgraph’s architecture has been built natively for in-memory data analysis and storage.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Being ACID compliant, it ensures consistency and reliability in its core design.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] However, Memgraph also offers flexibility with it’s other storage modes.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] By default, an empty instance will start using in-memory transactional storage mode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] To start Memgraph in the `ON_DISK_TRANSACTIONAL` or `IN_MEMORY_ANALYTICAL` storage node, change the `--storage-mode` configuration flag accordingly.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] You cannot switch from an in-memory storage mode to an on-disk storage mode when the database contains data.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] It is also impossible to start Memgraph in one storage mode and to load a snapshot image that was created with another storage mode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] When switching modes, Memgraph will wait until all other transactions are done.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If some other transactions are running in your system, you will receive a warning message, so be sure to set the log level at least to `WARNING`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Switching from the in-memory storage mode to the on-disk storage mode is allowed when there is only one active session and the database is empty.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] As Memgraph Lab uses multiple sessions to run queries in parallel, it is currently impossible to switch to the on-disk storage mode within Memgraph Lab.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] You can change the storage mode to on-disk transactional using `mgconsole`, then connect to the instance with Memgraph Lab and query the instance as usual.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] It is forbidden to change the storage mode from `ON_DISK_TRANSACTIONAL` to any of the in-memory storage modes while there is data in the database as it might not fit into the RAM.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] To change the storage mode to any of the in-memory storages, empty the instance and restart it.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] An empty database will start in the default storage mode (in-memory transactional) or the storage mode defined by the `--storage-mode` configuration flag.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If you are running the Memgraph Enterprise Edition, you need to have `STORAGE_MODE` permission to change the storage mode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Non-empty database using in-memory transactional or analytical storage mode will restart in transactional storage mode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This behavior can be changed using the `--storage-mode` configuration flag.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] But, regardless of what the flag is set to, a non-empty instance in the on-disk storage mode cannot change storage mode even upon restart.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The unscoped `SHOW STORAGE INFO` only reports `global_storage_mode`, which is the **startup-default** storage mode (the `--storage-mode` flag) and does **not** reflect runtime `STORAGE MODE …` changes.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] `IN_MEMORY_TRANSACTIONAL` storage mode offers all ACID guarantees.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] WAL files and periodic snapshots are created automatically, and you can also create snapshots manually.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the `IN_MEMORY_TRANSACTIONAL` mode, Memgraph creates a `Delta` object each time data is changed.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Deltas are the backbone upon which Memgraph provides atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability - ACID.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] By using `Deltas`, Memgraph creates write-ahead-logs for durability, provides isolation, consistency, and atomicity (by ensuring that everything is executed or nothing is).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Depending on the transaction isolation level, other transactions may see changes from other transactions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the transactional storage mode, snapshots are created periodically or manually.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] They capture the database state and store it on the disk.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] A snapshot is used to recover the database upon startup (depending on the setting of the configuration flag `--data-recovery-on-startup`, which defaults to `true`).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] When Memgraph starts creating a periodic snapshot, it is not possible to manually create a snapshot, until the periodic snapshot is created.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Snapshot creation requires a transactional view.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This can lead to spikes in memory consumption when data is being ingested in parallel to snapshot creation.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] It is possible to pause the periodic snapshot background job at run-time.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This can speed up ingestion time and lower memory usage.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Manual snapshots are created by running the `CREATE SNAPSHOT;` query.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the transactional storage mode, Memgraph is fully ACID compliant which could cause memory spikes during data import because each time data is changed Memgraph creates `Delta` objects to provides atomicity, consistency, isolation, and durability.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] But `Deltas` also require memory (56B per change), especially when there are a lot of changes (for example, during import with the `LOAD CSV` clause).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] By switching the storage mode to `IN_MEMORY_ANALYTICAL` mode disables the creation of `Deltas` thus drastically speeding up import with lower memory consumption - up to 6 times faster import and less memory consumption.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] As `Deltas` are the foundation for ACID properties, they provide information on what has changed in different concurrent transactions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] They also cause conflicts between transactions when multiple transactions change the same graph object.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] A typical scenario would be adding a relationship to the same node or adding a property to the same node.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the analytical storage mode, Memgraph does not create `Deltas`, and therefore, there won’t be any conflicts between transactions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Adding relationships is thread-safe, which means that **multiple transactions can add relationships to the same node without any conflicts**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] That leads to a very efficient import process in scenarios with a dense graph and supernode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] There are no `WAL` files created nor periodic snapshots.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Users **can** create a snapshot manually.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the analytical storage mode, there are no ACID guarantees and other transactions can see the changes of ongoing transactions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Also, a transaction can see the changes it is doing.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This means that the transactions can be committed in random orders, and the updates to the data, in the end, might not be correct.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The absence of isolation guarantees also implies that changes by parallel transactions may affect the correctness of query procedures that read from the graph.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The most critical case is that of the procedure returning a graph element (node or relationship), or a container type holding those.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Please note that deleting same part of the graph from parallel transaction will lead to undefined behavior.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Users developing custom query procedures and functions intended to work in the analytical storage mode should use API methods to check if Memgraph is running in a transactional (ACID-compliant) storage mode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If not, the query module APIs let you check whether graph elements (nodes and relationships) are deleted, and whether containers (maps, lists and paths) that may hold graph elements don’t contain any deleted values.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memgraph uses snapshots and write-ahead logs to ensure data durability and backup.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Snapshots capture the database state and store it on the disk.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] A snapshot is then used to recover the database upon startup (depending on the setting of the configuration flag `--data-recovery-on-startup`, which defaults to `true`).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In Memgraph, snapshots are created periodically or manually with `CREATE SNAPSHOT;` Cypher query.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the analytical storage mode, WAL files and periodic snapshots are **not created**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Before switching back to the in-memory transactional storage mode create a snapshot manually.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the in-memory analytical storage mode, Memgraph guarantees that creating a snapshot is **the only** transaction present in the system, and all the other transactions will wait until the snapshot is created to ensure its validity.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Once Memgraph switches to the in-memory transactional mode, it will restore data from the snapshot file and create a WAL for all new updates, if not otherwise instructed by the config file.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] These are some of the implications of not having ACID properties.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] But if you do not have write-heavy workload, and you want to run analytical queries that will not change the data, you can take advantage of the low memory costs of the analytical mode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] At the moment, the in-memory analytical storage mode **doesn’t support replication and high availability**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The on-disk transactional storage mode is still in the experimental phase.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] We recommend our users use in-memory storage modes whenever possible.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If you try out on-disk transactional storage mode and encounter an issue, please open it on our GitHub repository.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In case your data is larger than your RAM can handle, and you can’t continue with the in-memory storage modes, don’t hesitate to reach out to us and schedule an office hours call so we can advise you and help you.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Our goal is to improve the on-disk transactional storage mode in the future, so any feedback would be greatly appreciated.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the on-disk transactional storage mode, disk is used as a physical storage which allows you to save more data than the capacity of your RAM.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This helps keep the hardware costs to a minimum, but you should except slower performance when compared to the in-memory transactional storage mode.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Keep in mind that while executing queries, all the graph objects used in the transactions still need to be able to fit in the RAM, or Memgraph will throw an exception.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memgraph uses RocksDB as a background storage to serialize nodes and relationships into a key-value format.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The used architecture is also known as “larger than memory” as it enables in-memory databases to save more data than the main memory can hold, without the performance overhead caused by the buffer pool.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The imported data is residing on the disk, while the main memory contains two caches, one executing operations on main RocksDB instance and the other for operations that require indexes.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In both cases, Memgraph’s custom `SkipList` cache is used, which allows a multithreaded read-write access pattern.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Concurrent execution of transactions is supported differently for on-disk storage than for in-memory.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The in-memory storage mode relies on `Delta` objects which store the exact versions of data at the specific moment in time.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Therefore, the in-memory storage mode uses a pessimistic approach and immediately checks whether there is a conflict between two transactions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the on-disk storage mode, the cache is used per transaction.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This significantly simplifies object management since there is no need to question certain object’s validity, but it also requires the optimistic approach for conflict resolution between transactions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the on-disk storage mode, the conflict is checked at the transaction’s commit time with the help of RocksDB’s transaction support.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This also implies that Deltas are cleared after each transaction, which can optimize memory usage during execution.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Deltas are still used to fully support Cypher’s semantic of the write queries.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The design of the on-disk storage also simplifies the process of garbage collection, since all the data is on disk.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The on-disk storage mode supports only snapshot isolation level.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Mostly because it’s the Memgraph viewpoint that snapshot isolation should be the default isolation level for most applications relying on databases.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] But the snapshot isolation level also simplifies the query’s execution flow since no data is transferred to the disk until the commit of the transaction.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Label and label-property indexes are stored in separate RocksDB instances as key-value pairs so that the access to the data is faster.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Whenever the indexed node is accessed, it’s stored into a separate in-memory cache to maximize the reading speed.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] When it comes to constraints, the existence constraints don’t use context from the disk since the validity of nodes can be checked by looking only at this single node.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] On the other side, uniqueness constraints require a different approach.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] For a node to be valid, the engine needs to iterate through all other nodes under constraint and check whether a conflict exists.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] To speed up this iteration process, nodes under constraint are stored into a separate RocksDB instance to eliminate the cost of iterating over nodes which are not under constraint.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In the on-disk storage mode, durability is supported by RocksDB since it keeps its own WAL files.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memgraph persists the metadata used in the implementation of the on-disk storage.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If the workload is larger than memory, a single transaction must fit into the memory.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] A memory tracker tracks all allocations happening throughout the transaction’s lifetime.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Disk space also has to be carefully managed.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Since the timestamp is serialized together with the raw node and relationship data, the engine needs to ensure that when the new version of the same node is stored, the old one is deleted.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] At the moment, the on-disk storage **doesn’t support replication and high availability**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Below is the format in which data is serialized to the disk.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Value does not contain `indexing label`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memgraph on-disk storage supports the `EDGE IMPORT MODE` to import relationships with high throughput.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] When the database is in this mode, only relationships can be created and modified.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Any operation on nodes other than read are prohibited and will throw an exception.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] When importing data using a CSV file, import nodes and relationships separately.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Currently, to import relationships as fast as possible, **don’t create indexes**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Here is an example how to import data using the LOAD CSV clause.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] For files containing Cypher queries (.cypherql), create all nodes, then activate the `EDGE IMPORT MODE` and create relationships.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Indexes can be created before or after activating the `EDGE IMPORT MODE`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] It’s best to **create a label-property index** on node properties used to match nodes that will be connected with a relationship.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Estimating Memgraph’s storage memory usage is not entirely straightforward because it depends on a lot of variables, but it is possible to do so quite accurately.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] You can also use the Storage memory calculator.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Let’s test this formula on the Marvel Comic Universe Social Network dataset, which is also available as a dataset inside Memgraph Lab and contains 21,723 vertices and 682,943 edges.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Now, let’s run an empty Memgraph instance on a x86 Ubuntu.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] It consumes **~75MB** of RAM due to baseline runtime overhead.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Once the dataset is loaded, RAM usage rises up to **~260MB**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memory usage primarily consists of storage and query execution memory usage.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] After executing `FREE MEMORY` query to force the cleanup of query execution, the RAM usage drops to **~200MB**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If the baseline runtime overhead of **75MB** is subtracted from the total memory usage of the dataset, which is **200MB**, and storage memory usage comes up to **~125MB**, which shows that the formula is correct.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Let’s dive deeper into the `IN_MEMORY_TRANSACTIONAL` storage mode memory usage values.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Because Memgraph works on the x86 architecture, calculations are based on the x86 Linux memory usage.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] For the latest and most precise memory layout please clone Memgraph and use, e.g., pahole to discover accurate information.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each `Vertex` and `Edge` object has a pointer to a `Delta` object.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The `Delta` object stores all changes on a certain `Vertex` or `Edge` and that’s why `Vertex` and `Edge` memory usage will be increased by the memory of the `Delta` objects they are pointing to.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If there are few updates, there are also few `Delta` objects because the latest data is stored in the object.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] But, if the database has a lot of concurrent operations, many `Delta` objects will be created.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Of course, the `Delta` objects will be kept in memory as long as needed, and a bit more, because of the internal GC inefficiencies.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each `Delta` object has a least **56B**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each `Vertex` object has at least **80B** + **56B** for the `Delta` object, in total, a minimum of **136B**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Keep in mind that three labels take as much space as four labels, and five to seven labels take as much space as eight labels, etc., due to the dynamic memory allocation.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each `Edge` object has at least **32B** + **56B** for the `Delta` object, in total, a minimum of **88B**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each object (`Vertex`, `Edge`) is placed inside a data structure called a `SkipList`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The `SkipList` has an additional overhead in terms of `SkipListNode` structure and `next_pointers`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each `SkipListNode` has an additional **8B** element overhead and another **8B** for each of the `next_pointers`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] It is impossible to know the exact number of **next_pointers** upfront, and consequently the total size, but it’s never more than **double the number of objects** because the number of pointers is generated by binomial distribution (take a look at the source code for details).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each `LabelIndex::Entry` object has exactly **16B**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Depending on the actual value stored, each `LabelPropertyIndex::Entry` has at least **72B**.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Objects of both types are placed into the `SkipList`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] All properties use **1B** for metadata - type, size of property ID and the size of payload in the case of `NULL` and `BOOLEAN` values, or size of payload size indicator for other types (how big is the stored value, for example, integers can be 1B, 2B 4B or 8b depending on their value).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Then they take up **another byte** for storing property ID, which means each property takes up at least 2B.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] After those 2B, some properties (for example, `STRING` values) store addition metadata.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] And lastly, all properties store the value.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] $\texttt{propertySize} = \texttt{basicMetadata} + \texttt{propertyID} + [\texttt{additionalMetadata}] + \texttt{value}.$ propertySize=basicMetadata+propertyID+[additionalMetadata]+value.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Users can additionally inspect the exact size of a property in bytes using the propertySize() function.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The Marvel dataset consists of `Hero`, `Comic` and `ComicSeries` labels, which are indexed.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] There are also three label-property indexes - on the `name` property of `Hero` and `Comic` vertices, and on the `title` property of `ComicSeries` vertices.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The `ComicSeries` vertices also have the `publishYear` property.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] There are 6487 `Hero` and 12,661 `Comic` vertices with the property `name`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] $\texttt{NumberOfVertices} \times (\texttt{Vertex} + \texttt{properties} + \texttt{SkipListNode} + \texttt{next\_pointers} + \texttt{Delta}).$ NumberOfVertices×(Vertex+properties+SkipListNode+next_pointers+Delta).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Let’s assume the name on average has $3\text{B}+10\text{B} = 13\text{B}$ 3B+10B=13B (each name is on average 10 characters long).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The remaining 2,584 vertices are the `ComicSeries` vertices with the `title` and `publishYear` properties.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Let’s assume that the `title` property is approximately the same length as the `name` property.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The `publishYear` property is a list of integers.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The average length of the `publishYear` list is 2.17, let’s round it up to 3 elements.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Since the year is an integer, 2B for each integer will be more than enough, plus the 2B for the metadata.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] $\texttt{NumberOfEdges} \times (\texttt{Edge} + \texttt{SkipListNode} + \texttt{next\_pointers} + \texttt{Delta}).$ NumberOfEdges×(Edge+SkipListNode+next_pointers+Delta).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] There are 682,943 edges in the Marvel dataset.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Next, `Hero`, `Comic` and `ComicSeries` labels have label indexes.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] $\texttt{NumberOfLabelIndices} \times \texttt{NumberOfVertices} \times (\texttt{SkipListNode<LabelIndex::Entry>} + \texttt{next\_pointers}).$ NumberOfLabelIndices×NumberOfVertices×(SkipListNode<LabelIndex::Entry>+next_pointers).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] For label-property index, labeled property needs to be taken into account.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Property `name` is indexed on `Hero` and `Comic` vertices, while property `title` is indexed on `ComicSeries` vertices.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] We already assumed that the `title` property is approximately the same length as the `name` property.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] $\texttt{NumberOfLabelPropertyIndices} \times \texttt{NumberOfVertices} \times (\texttt{SkipListNode<LabelIndex::Entry>} + \texttt{property} + \texttt{next\_pointers}).$ NumberOfLabelPropertyIndices×NumberOfVertices×(SkipListNode<LabelIndex::Entry>+property+next_pointers).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Bear in mind the number can vary because objects can have higher overhead due to the additional data.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In Memgraph, you can control memory usage by limiting, inspecting and deallocating memory.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] By setting the `--memory-limit` flag in the configuration file, you can set the maximum amount of memory (in MiB) that a Memgraph instance can allocate during its runtime.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If the memory limit is exceeded, only the queries that don’t require additional memory are allowed.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If the memory limit is exceeded while a query is running, the query is aborted and its transaction becomes invalid.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The effective allocation limit (shown as `memory_limit` in `SHOW STORAGE INFO`) is set to the **lower** of the `--memory-limit` configuration flag and the Enterprise license memory limit.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This limit applies to the entire Memgraph instance across all databases.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] To set a per-database / per-tenant memory limit (which also covers query memory usage against a single database), visit Tenant Profiles.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If the flag is set to 0, it will use the default values.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] All allocations inside query are counted from intermediary results to allocations made while creating nodes and relationships.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In some cases, intermediate results are aggregated to return valid query results and the query execution memory can end up using a large amount of RAM.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Keep in mind that query execution memory monotonically grows in size during the execution, and it’s freed once the query execution is done.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] A general rule of thumb is to have double the RAM than what the actual dataset is occupying.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If you use the `LIMIT` option, you have to specify the amount of memory a query can allocate for its execution.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] You can use this clause in a query only once at the end of the query.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The limit is applied to the entire query.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If you use the `LIMIT` option, you can specify the amount of memory that the called procedure can allocate for its execution.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If you use the `UNLIMITED` option, no memory restrictions will be imposed when the procedure is called.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If you don’t specify the clause, the memory limit is set to a default value of 100 MB.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] One procedure call can have only one `PROCEDURE MEMORY` clause at the end of the call.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If a query contains multiple procedure calls, each call can have its own limit specification.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The unscoped `SHOW STORAGE INFO` returns only instance-level fields.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] For per-database metrics (such as `vertex_count`, `edge_count`, the live `storage_mode` and per-database memory trackers), use `SHOW STORAGE INFO ON CURRENT DATABASE` or `SHOW STORAGE INFO ON DATABASE <name>`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Find out more about `SHOW STORAGE INFO` query on Server stats.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] In multi-tenant deployments, Memgraph Enterprise tracks memory for each database independently.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Each database’s allocations are counted against both the database’s own limit and the global instance limit, ensuring no single database can starve others of resources.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Storage, query execution, and vector index allocations are all attributed to the database that originated them, giving a complete picture of per-database memory usage.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Their editions and privileges differ — see the availability note below.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] `ON CURRENT DATABASE` targets the session’s currently-selected database, while `ON DATABASE <name>` targets a named database.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Both return the full per-database field set (storage stats, isolation level, storage mode and the memory trackers).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] For the complete list of per-database fields (including `name`, `database_uuid`, `storage_mode`, `vertex_count`, `edge_count`, `average_degree`, `unreleased_delta_objects`, `disk_usage` and `storage_isolation_level`), see Per-database storage information.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Both per-database `SHOW STORAGE INFO` variants require the `STATS` privilege.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] `SHOW STORAGE INFO ON CURRENT DATABASE` and `SHOW STORAGE INFO ON DATABASE` for the **default** database work in all editions; targeting a **non-default** database via `ON DATABASE <name>` requires the Memgraph Enterprise Edition.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] `SHOW MEMORY INFO` requires no privilege beyond a valid Enterprise license and is available only in the Memgraph Enterprise Edition.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The per-database `query_memory_tracked` field tracks only **runtime memory** — intermediate results, aggregations, and operator state during query execution.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] It does **not** include storage allocations made by the query (those are counted in `graph_memory_tracked`).
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This is different from the `QUERY MEMORY LIMIT` clause, which caps both runtime and storage allocations together.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Per-database memory limits are enforced via tenant profiles.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] When a limit is hit, any query that would allocate memory beyond the cap is rejected — read queries are not exempt.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If you don’t have properties on relationships, disable them in the configuration file by setting the `--storage-properties-on-edges` flag to `false`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This can significantly reduce memory usage because effectively `Edge` objects will not be created, and all information will be inlined under `Vertex` objects.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] You can disable properties on relationships with a non-empty database, if the relationships are without properties.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Another way to reduce memory usage is through property compression.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This feature compresses the entire `PropertyStore` object, meaning it compresses all compressible properties in the database.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] When property store compression is enabled, it checks if the `PropertyStore` of a vertex can be compressed, and if it can, it compresses it using the well-known compression library `zlib`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] To enable compression, set the `--storage-property-store-compression-enabled` flag to `true`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The default value of this flag is `false`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Additionally, users can control the compression level with the `--storage-property-store-compression-level` flag.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The default value is mid, but two other values, low and high, are also available.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The low setting compresses properties minimally, reducing memory usage slightly, while the high setting compresses properties the most, trying to maximize memory savings.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] However, there’s a tradeoff to consider: higher compression levels can reduce performance.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Therefore, users focused on maintaining optimal performance may prefer not to set it to `high`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Keep in mind that even though it can reduce memory usage, compression can impact query performance.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] For workloads with many `DOUBLE` properties, you can reduce their storage size by lowering the floating-point precision via the `--storage-floating-point-resolution-bits` flag.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The allowed values are `64` (default), `32`, and `16`, corresponding to double, float, and half precision respectively.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] WAL files and snapshots always serialize `DOUBLE` values as full 64-bit IEEE 754, so the durability format itself is resolution-independent.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] However, precision is baked in at write time: WAL and snapshot entries store the value that `GetProperty()` returns, which is already truncated to the active resolution.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] If exact round-trip fidelity is required, set the resolution before loading data and do not change it afterwards.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memgraph has a garbage collector that deallocates unused objects, thus freeing the memory.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The rate of the garbage collection in seconds can be specified in the configuration file by setting the `--storage-gc-cycle-sec`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] This query tries to clean up as much unused memory as possible without affecting currently running transactions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] Memgraph uses a `jemalloc` allocator to handle all allocations and to track allocations happening in the system.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The default operating system limits on `mmap` counts are likely to be too low, which may result in out-of-memory exceptions.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] To increase this value permanently, update the `vm.max_map_count` setting in */etc/sysctl.conf*.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] To verify, reboot the system and run `sysctl vm.max_map_count`.
[src:memgraph/storage-memory-usage] The RPM and Debian packages will configure this setting automatically so you don’t need to do any more configurations.
